But there is another category of people - those who are able to sleep half as much and still continue to work productively. üò±Scientists call them "slow sleepers". 1-3% of the world's population sleep 4-5 hours a day and wake up not by an alarm clock, but simply because they no longer want to sleep, and they do this for their entire lives. Source of the problem is a rare genetic abnormality. At the same time, low-sleep people do not have health problems, unlike people who consciously adjust their sleep time downwards, reducing the sleep time to 6 or less hours. There are far more people in the world who consider themselves to get too little sleep than the" official " 1-3 %. At the same time, scientists believe, that trying to change or alter the body‚Äôs natural need for sleep, given by nature, is as unrealistic as, for example, to increase or decrease the size of one‚Äôs leg.¬†Psychotherapist Oleg Chaban believes that such sleep disorders are a disease of successful people. A person pays for lack of sleep with numerous I‚Äôll health consequences including, but not limited to: obesity, impaired memory and attention, accelerated aging, and the risk of heart disease, diabetes, and cancer. Therefore, many psychologists call for people to return to normal eight hour sleep patterns, considering that the fashion for neglecting sleep for the sake of work or entertainment to be very dangerous. Among the "sleepless" are such notable figures as Leonardo da Vinci, Salvador Dali, Nikola Tesla, Margaret¬†Thatcher and Madonna.
